    <center><table class="itemDisplayTable">
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Title:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Sterilization of Papaya Pulp by Alternative Preservation Methods</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Authors:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Amita Tokas, Mrityunjay Anand<br />Shilpa Zhamnani, Smita Kumari</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Keywords:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Sterilization of Papaya Pulp<br />Alternative Preservation Methods</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Issue Date:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">May-2009 </td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Publisher:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">SRM University</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Series/Report no.:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">P4354</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Abstract:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Preservation techniques in the food industry ensure product safety and shelf life stability.
Heat is the most common way to inactivate microorganisms and enzymes, but may result in
the manufacture of low quality product. Moreover, consumers demand higher quality food
products, which eventually lead to utilizing alternative preservation processes. Preservation
by Ultrasonic treatment at low frequency combined with thermal treatment results in higher
microbial inactivation and enhances shelf life without altering the sensory characters and
nutrient content. Ohmic heating of food products is another beneficial technique in providing
rapid, indirect and uniform heating, resulting in less thermal damage to the product. The
objective of this project was to examine the effect of two different alternative preservation
methods i.e. ultrasound and ohmic heating individually on papaya pulp upon storage and to
study various physico-chemical properties of fresh pulp as well as the treated one. Freshly
prepared papaya pulp was subjected to an ultrasonic treatment at different time- temperature
-frequency combinations and ohmic heating at various voltage combinations. After each
treatment the effect of various parameters was observed and evaluated on the treated pulp.
Based on all nutritional and antimicrobial analysis, it was found that ultrasound combined
with thermal process gives better quality product as compared to conventional method. The
TSS value of the raw sample taken for ultrasound and ohmic heating was 5.26 ºB and 11.2 ºB
respectively, which was reduced to 4.49 ºB and 7.3 ºB respectively over the storage period.
Good results were obtained for the samples treated by ultrasound at low frequency (90 ºC for
30 minutes) with the TSS of 4.93 ºB after 30 days and the samples treated by ohmic heating
at high voltage (100 and 120 V), the values were 10.2 ºB and 10.4 ºB respectively after 20
days. Ascorbic acid is an important nutritional component of papaya and the values obtained
for the raw sample were 57.14 mg and 58.82 mg for ultrasound and ohmic heating
respectively. Slight changes were observed for the sample treated with ultrasound, the value
was 52.63 mg over the storage period. However for ohmic heating, changes were more due to
heating but less change was observed for the sample treated at high voltage. This is attributed
to less processing time of the sample and the value after storage was 52.63 mg. The samples
treated with ultrasound showed an initial increase in the total sugar content after 10 days
storage and the values were reduced during further storage period. Initially the value was
8.55 gm. Treatment carried out at low frequency (90 ºC, 30 minutes) gave better result in
terms of more retention of total sugar. The values obtained were 13.2 gm after 10 days and
11.8 gm after 30 days. On the other hand there was continuous decrease in the total sugar
content over storage period for the samples treated with ohmic heating. The initial value was
14.1gm and minimum changes were observed for the sample treated at high voltage (100 and
120 V) with the final value of 13.1gm and 13.2 gm respectively. An improved textural
appearance and flavor retention was observed in ohmically heated products and a higher
reduction in microbial count, nutrient retention and enhanced shelf life was achieved by
ultrasonic preservation. Hence, the potential use of ultrasound and ohmic heating as an
alternative preservation process was demonstrated on papaya pulp over a storage period of
one month. Further research can be conducted on combination of both the technologies and
the effects can be studied.</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">URI:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue"><a href="http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/10647">http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/10647</a></td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Appears in Collections:</td><td class="metadataFieldValue"><a href="/dspace/handle/123456789/10645">2009</a><br/></td></tr>
</table></center><br/>
